Headline::::
Eddie Jones v Warren Gatland – how do the two head coaches compare?




DateTime::::2016-03-09T13:43:31+0000



<p><span class="drop-cap"><span class="drop-cap__inner">I</span></span>t has been a quiet 10 days or so for those anxious for their Six Nations fix. The fallow weeks are always hard, but often leavened by a choice word from a wily coach hoping to gain a psychological edge somewhere. Unfortunately, Eddie Jones has not yet obliged since the last round and <a class="u-underline" data-component="auto-linked-tag" data-link-name="auto-linked-tag" href="http://www.theguardian.com/sport/warren-gatland">Warren Gatland</a> was understated in his sole appearance of the England v Wales buildup on Tuesday.</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/mar/09/england-hooker-jamie-george-injured-wales-six-nations-rugby">England hooker Jamie George out of Six Nations match with Wales</a> </p>

<p>Gatland makes minimal media appearances these days. Meanwhile, Jones announced in dramatic style after the England-Ireland match that <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/feb/27/eddie-jones-grand-slam-england-wales" title="">he would not be talking to the press</a> in the build-up to the Wales match, his Ziggy Stardust-at-the-Hammersmith Odeon moment. More than a few looks were exchanged of the did-he-just-say-what-I-think-he-said variety. In fact, Jones will make an appearance on Thursday, back by popular demand, but his absence has merely highlighted the extent to which he has so quickly installed himself alongside Gatland as a much-cherished/derided piece of the Six Nations furniture. Saturday’s showdown between England and Wales will be the first between the two coaches who elicit more in the way of extreme reactions than any others, so how do they compare?</p>

<p>Hookers operate in the heart of the most brutal environment in the sport – the scrum – and yet they are usually smaller than the men around them. Gatland and Jones played their careers in the No2 jersey without ever winning a Test cap for New Zealand or Australia respectively. They will have needed a certain spikiness to survive and, dare we say it, a touch of the cerebral, not to mention the Zen-like ability to rise above the fearful poundings and perform the most high-precision task in rugby – the lineout throw. It forges a special breed, and they often go on to prove excellent coaches, both for results and provocative copy. Think Richard Cockerill and Steve Diamond, the northern equivalents.</p>

<p>Jones has one big gong over Gatland – a World Cup winners’ medal, picked up in 2007 when he was technical adviser to South Africa. He also has another World Cup final to his name, this time <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2003/nov/23/rugbyworldcup2003.rugbyunion5" title="">as head coach of Australia</a> in 2003, as well as a Tri Nations title with the same in 2001, his first season. His Brumbies team around the turn of the millennium were pretty special, too. And then there was <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/sep/19/south-africa-japan-rugby-world-cup-2015-match-report" title="">the Miracle of Japan</a>.</p>

<p>Gatland’s record as head coach, however, is the more consistent. At least it is since 2002, when he joined a Wasps team rooted to the bottom of the Premiership. They were English champions for the next three seasons, and European in 2004. Then he joined Waikato and won the National Provincial Championship at the first attempt. Next, to Wales: <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/mar/16/rugbyunion.sixnations1" title="">grand slam at the first attempt</a>. British &amp; Irish Lions: <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/jul/07/five-reasons-lions-warren-gatland-australia" title="">series winners at first attempt</a> (as head coach). He clearly has a knack for making a first impression. His critics will point to Wales’s record against the southern hemisphere, but, really, they are not alone in struggling against that lot. Some might say it is a mental block among the players that has prevented Wales turning more of their increasingly narrow and “heartbreaking” defeats into victories. Some of those matches looked harder to lose than win. Against each other, they have met once, although never as head coaches – Gatland was technical adviser to the Chiefs in 2007 when they beat Jones’s Reds in Brisbane by two points.</p>

<p>For immediate results, Gatland’s the man; for the longer term, then Jones. The latter is renowned for a brutal management style. The legend goes that he tries to crush his players, and those who do not break will become champions. He is also a talent-spotter of considerable perception. These qualities can take time to produce results. His first year in charge of the Brumbies was a disaster, as was the single year he spent in charge of the Reds in 2007. His spell in charge of Saracens was none too flash, either. All of them went on to be champion sides. The noises coming out of the England camp speak of a gentler approach than the above might suggest, which is not surprising given he was straight into a short, sharp championship he would do well to win. So far, so good. The man himself has said he is mellower now, following <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/nov/29/japan-coach-jones-returns-from-stroke" title="">the stroke he suffered in 2013</a>.</p>

<p>Gatland does not have quite as fierce a reputation, but he is utterly ruthless when he perceives a means‑end decision that needs to be taken, regardless of emotion. The <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/jul/08/lions-2013-brian-odriscoll-australia" title="">Brian O’Driscoll non-selection</a> on the 2013 Lions tour will remain the most famous example, but <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/jan/25/adams-jones-retires-wales-six-nations-omission" title="">Adam Jones</a> is among a host of others who will testify to a lack of sentimentality. Gatland’s strength lies in simplifying matters with special emphasis on fitness.</p>

<p>Warrenball, insofar as it exists, is little more than a summary of what the modern game has become – big men trying to get over the gainline. Admittedly, it has had some bad press of late, but if you have 17st three‑quarters who can run hard you let them do it. With Wasps, Gatland had a lighter back division and devised a different gameplan, which revolved around reassembling his three‑quarter line after multiple phases, so that they could strike against a mis-shapen defence.</p>

<p>Gatland and Jones, like all the best coaches, are masters of working with what they have. Jones’s Japan side at the World Cup were one of the most obviously well-coached teams that have ever played – technical excellence and players who all seemed to know exactly what they were supposed to do at any given moment, none of whom were stars. With England he has had less time and bigger personalities, but already a pattern is discernible somewhere between the Japanese and Welsh templates. If you have a Billy Vunipola you send him hurtling at the gainline; if you have George Ford and Owen Farrell in midfield you send out long passes when the opposition are narrow. It is not revolutionary, but it is the shrewd deployment of resources that marks out the best coaches.</p>

<p>What would happen if they met for a beer? People can be very different in such a scenario, but you sense that Jones would supply the fire, Gatland the ice. Both can hurt in their different ways. Over the microphones, Jones fixes his questioner from under angular eyebrows constantly on the move. “It’s a stupid question, mate” is one of his catchphrases, but a vulnerable side has been revealed by his self-imposed media ban. He is a straight-talker. They often find themselves in trouble, and he knows it, but he cannot do the boring thing either. “I can’t win,” he pleaded after Ireland, “so it’s easiest if I don’t come to the press conferences.”</p>

<p>Gatland, too, was poignant at the <a class="u-underline" data-component="auto-linked-tag" data-link-name="auto-linked-tag" href="http://www.theguardian.com/sport/sixnations">Six Nations</a> launch when asked why he was less provocative in the media these days. Unlike Jones, his face barely moves when he talks, his words, provocative or not, falling softly from the side of his mouth. “It got to the point where it was so depressing, thinking, ‘that was a really good interview’. The journalist’s written a really good article, but someone picks one little piece out of it to turn it into a headline, and you spend the next 48 hours fire-fighting. It takes the enjoyment out of it completely.”</p>

<p>Love them or loathe them, Gatland and Jones are just two fiercely driven men trying to do their jobs in a very noisy world. It may have been quiet without them these past few days, but they are supplying us with a compelling narrative, which will reach its pitch when they go head to head for the first time on Saturday. Their world is about to get a whole lot noisier.</p>




